==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/stæŋ/}}

===Etymology 1===
From Old Norse ''[[stǫng]]'' (cognate with Old English ''[[steng]]'').

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A long [[bar]]; a [[pole]]; a [[shaft]]; a [[stake]].
#:*'''1962''': Gripping the '''stang''', she peered / At ghostly trees.  Bus stopped.  Bus disappeared. — Vladimir Nabokov, ''Pale Fire''
# In land measure, a [[pole]], [[rod]], or [[perch]].

===Etymology 2===
From Old Norse ''[[stanga]]'' ‘prick, goad’.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# ''(obsolete, intransitive)'' to shoot with pain, to [[sting]]
# ''(obsolete, transitive)'' to [[spear]]; to [[sting]]

===Etymology 3===
From [[sting]].

====Verb====
'''stang'''
* past tense of [[sting]]

